yIf the tick mark appears white, it's likely due to the default background color blending with the design. Here's an improved implementation using an SVG tick mark, ensuring it remains visible regardless of the background:

Updated Solution: SVG Tick Mark with #007bff

SCSS for Styling

.selected-label {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  color: #007bff;
  font-weight: bold;

  .tick {
    width: 16px;
    height: 16px;
    margin-left: 5px;

    svg {
      fill: #007bff;
      width: 100%;
      height: 100%;
    }
  }
}

Updated HTML Example

<div class="selected-label">
  SELECTED
  <span class="tick">
    <svg
      xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
      viewBox="0 0 24 24"
      fill="none"
      stroke="#007bff"
      stroke-width="2"
      stroke-linecap="round"
      stroke-linejoin="round"
    >
      <polyline points="20 6 9 17 4 12" />
    </svg>
  </span>
</div>

Key Notes

1. The tick mark is represented as an inline SVG for consistent visibility.


2. The color #007bff is applied to the stroke attribute of the SVG.


3. The polyline inside the SVG creates the checkmark shape.



Alternative CSS-Only Solution

If you don't want to use an SVG, you can use pure CSS with a pseudo-element:

.selected-label {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  color: #007bff;
  font-weight: bold;

  .tick {
    position: relative;
    display: inline-block;
    width: 10px;
    height: 10px;
    margin-left: 5px;

    &:before {
      content: '';
      position: absolute;
      width: 5px;
      height: 10px;
      border: solid #007bff;
      border-width: 0 2px 2px 0;
      transform: rotate(45deg);
      left: 0;
      top: 0;
    }
  }
}

HTML for CSS-Only Solution

<div class="selected-label">
  SELECTED
  <span class="tick"></span>
</div>

This should render a visible tick mark in blue (#007bff). Let me know which one works best for your use case!

